commentBody:
@Lewis

 Very glad to see you back to your daily commentary and weekly clue summary. You are the gem of this forum and an example of how to always strive to be positive. Thanks for all you do on a daily basis.

But, how does a yoga instructor end up with back surgery? This doesn’t seem fair!

@Andrew

Not all unreturned serves are aces, but all aces are unreturned serves.

It fits.

@Heidi

It’s interesting, that logic. It works sometimes but
not others, and I think there’s some convention to it. If the clue was “an animal” and the answer was ZEBRA you’d balk at it (even though al zebras are animals) because you understood the clue was asking for some sort of synonym. But if I said “a black and white animal” you’d say ok to ZEBRA, even though there are pandas and white tigers, because you understood the clue was asking for “an example of a black and white animal” and not a term equivalent to all black and white animals. I don’t take the ACE clue that way, I take it as “a term that means the same as unreturned serve” and (if you are talking about tennis and not volleyball) that’s just not the case. So I’m more in Andrew’s camp about that, from a logic point of view. But it brings up an interesting semantic quandary about what is the switch in our brain which interprets those clues differently—apparently some sort of specificity issue but at what point and is it different for different people?

@Heidi

Again, I just think that it depends how you interpret the clue, and whether it’s narrowed down enough or not. In tennis, an unreturned serve is MORE often than not, not an ace. The football clue is more accurate because a quarterback tackle IS more often than not a SACK. But we are splitting hairs here. I think the point of pointing out the nits is more informational and FYI 
than really having an issue with the clue, for me at least.

@Andrew

If we're really picking nits, many serves that are unreturned and untouched in tennis are *not* ACES.

That is, when the serve is a fault or a let.

@SP

If the clue were "Tackle of the quarterback, usually" the correct answer (for the last few years) would be:

UNNECESSARY ROUGHNESS.

